ially%20broken%20by%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fchallenger-video-nasa-space-shuttle-program-2016-1%5C%22%3ESpace%20Shuttles%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20SpaceX%20continued%20working%20toward%20reusability%20with%20its%20Falcon%20series%20of%20rockets.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EUnfortunately%2C%20it%20is%20unclear%20how%20many%20Falcon%209%20rockets%20exist.%20What%20we%20do%20know%20is%20that%20the%20family%20of%20rockets%20has%20been%20involved%20in%20241%20launches%20and%20that%20failures%20are%20rare.%20In%202015%2C%20one%20rocket%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fspacex-just-failed-at-its-third-attempt-to-make-history-and-its-reusable-rocket-just-exploded-to-bits-2015-6%5C%22%3Erocket%20exploded%3C%2Fa%3E%20during%20flight%2C%20and%20the%20next%20year%20another%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fspacex-rocket-exploded-falcon-9-2016-9%5C%22%3EFalcon%209%20exploded%3C%2Fa%3E%20during%20tests.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20Falcon%209%20family%20of%20rockets%20is%20still%20in%20active%20use%20today%2C%20with%20the%20latest%20%E2%80%93%20the%20Block%205%20%E2%80%93%20flying%20178%20successful%20missions.%20According%20to%20SpaceX%2C%20the%20Falcon%209%20is%20the%20%26quot%3Bworld's%20first%20orbital%20class%20reusable%20rocket.%26quot%3B%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20Falcon%209%20Block%205%20is%20229.6%20feet%20tall%20and%20weighs%2038%2C000%20pounds%20by%20the%20time%20it%20touches%20down%20on%20an%20Autonomous%20Spaceport%20Drone%20Ship%20(ASDS)%20at%20the%20end%20of%20a%20mission.%20With%20a%20mass%20of%20more%20than%201.2%20million%20pounds%20fully%20loaded%2C%20it%20is%20fueled%20by%20rocket-grade%20kerosene%20(RP-1)%20and%20liquid%20oxygen.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIts%20engines%20give%20it%20in%20excess%20of%201.7%20million%20pounds%20of%20thrust%20at%20sea%20level%2C%20which%20creates%20the%20capability%20of%20lifting%2050%2C265%20pounds%20into%20low%20Earth%20orbit%20and%20could%20lift%2C%20according%20to%2